---


---

<h1 id="the-search-for-the-epicene-pronoun">The Search for the Epicene Pronoun</h1>
<blockquote>
<p>Dan Gerrity, June 2024</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Of the 7,164 world languages cataloged by Ethnologue in 2022,<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn1" id="fnref1">1</a></sup> 454 are living languages descended from Proto-Indo-European (“PIE”)<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn2" id="fnref2">2</a></sup>. Although fractional in number, roughly half of all humans today speak a PIE descendant, with nearly one billion speaking a Romance Language and half a billion speaking a Germanic language, including Modern English (“English”).</p>
<p>The complexity of PIE and its contemporary derivative languages is significant. While PIE had neither definite nor indefinite articles (e.g., <em>the</em>, <em>a(n)</em>), its complexity was driven primarily by gender and case, creating an intricate system of inflections to convey grammatical relationships and meanings.</p>
<p>A word about <em>gender</em>, a powerful word used when describing languages. Corbett, a linguistic scholar who has extensively studied and written about gender, makes an important observation regarding the term: “Genders are classes of nouns reflected in the behavior of associated words…. The classification frequently corresponds to a real-world distinction of sex, at least in part…(‘gender’ derives etymologically from Latin <em>genus</em>, via Old French <em>gender</em>, and originally meant ‘kind’ or ‘sort’).”<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn3" id="fnref3">3</a></sup> The importance of the history of the word gender lies in its essence as a classification or organization tool for the human mind, presumably to aid in pattern matching.  The word <em>gender</em> has historically been used as a means of categorization and it is possible that only in more recent millennia has it come to be associated with biological sex. Another gender scholar, Don Killian, asserts, “Gender assignment is largely arbitrary, even for the highest segments of the animacy hierarchy, where one could expect to find assignment based on salient features of the referent (such as sex).”<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn4" id="fnref4">4</a></sup></p>
<p>Further related to gender is the term <em>epicene</em>, defined by the Oxford English Dictionary (“OED”) as “[Adj.] 1. Grammar. In Latin and ancient Greek grammar: designating a class of nouns which may denote either males or females but which have a fixed grammatical gender (masculine, feminine, neuter, etc.); of or relating to such nouns. Hence in modern English and other languages: designating nouns and pronouns which may denote individuals of either sex; of or relating to such nouns. Cf. common adj. A.IV.18a. c1450–”<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn5" id="fnref5">5</a></sup>.</p>
<p>Linguistics scholars use the word <em>epicene</em> to describe effectively a non-gendered word substituting for one that is gendered: Greville Corbett explains, “Epicene nouns are therefore those which denote sexed beings but which do not differentiate them according to sex…. The existence of two separate nouns or of just one is a matter of lexis and morphology [and not] gender.”<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn6" id="fnref6">6</a></sup>  Thus an epicene pronoun would be one used to refer to a noun without implying the “sex” or “gender” of the referent.</p>
<p>PIE relied on gender and inflected word forms (e.g., endings and stem changes) to indicate distinctions in case, number, gender, tense, mood, voice, and aspect. PIE had <strong>eight</strong> cases for inflection purposes: Nominative (subject), Accusative (direct object), Dative (indirect object), Genitive (possessive), Locative, Instrumental, and Vocative. PIE cases were applied to nouns using three genders (masculine, feminine, and neuter) and three numbers (singular, dual,<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn7" id="fnref7">7</a></sup> plural<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn8" id="fnref8">8</a></sup>), yielding 72 possibilities for inflecting a noun such that it is in agreement with its context<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn9" id="fnref9">9</a></sup>.</p>
<p>As PIE moved into Proto-Germanic (“PG”), an ancestor of English, inflectional complexity was retained.  PG nouns were inflected across five cases, two numbers, and three genders, yielding 54 possibilities of inflection for a noun. See further this example in Hochdeutsch (Modern Standard German, or simply “German”),<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn10" id="fnref10">10</a></sup> which shows some of Modern German’s 24 possible inflectional combination of nouns.  Verbs in German are conjugated over two tenses, three moods, one voice, one aspect, three persons, and two numbers, yielding 36 syntactically indicated conjugations.</p>
