</table><p>Few of the 454 living PIE descendants have as little gendering, inflection, and conjugational complexity as English<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn11" id="fnref11">11</a></sup>. Dressler and colleagues quoted by Marzi define a strict ordering in PIE derivatives running from Lithuanian → Greek → Russian → Croation → Spanish → German → Dutch → French → English, with English being the least complex[^marzi]. Moreover, the closest cousins to English are in the Germanic family (German, Dutch, Scandinavian, etc.), are all tri-gender (masculine, feminine, and neuter), and heavily inflected. Consider that English lacks gendered nouns, has only two patterns for regular verb conjugation, does not inflect definite and indefinite articles, requires no agreement for adjectives and prescribes only a few cases (common, genitive, and object), some actually disappearing. McWhorter, who writes extensively on the remarkable simplification of English over time<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn12" id="fnref12">12</a></sup>, claims English is among the simplest modern languages in the world in terms of inflectional complexity, and lack of gender is a patent outlier.  Truly, the only remaining formal markers of gender in English outside of sex-specific nouns like woman and man,<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn13" id="fnref13">13</a></sup> are the third-person personal pronouns as follows:<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn14" id="fnref14">14</a></sup></p>
