<h2 id="the-case-for-gender-in-english">The Case for Gender in English</h2>
<p>It turns out that formidable reasons still exist to inspire movement toward a gender-free language in general a set of epicene personal pronouns in specific. Firstly, scholars such as Corbett make a compelling case that English is, in fact, a gendered language<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn16" id="fnref16">16</a></sup>.  To my surprise, yet making complete sense in retrospect, Natsuki, Atagi <em>et. al.</em> have studied how speakers of languages without formal noun and/or adjectival gendering effectively <u>impute their own genders</u>.  In other words, conceptualizing genders is possibly something anchored in the thinking of <em>homo sapiens</em> independent of language rather than as a result of well-understood syntactical or semantic rules imposed on thought by language encoding. It appears reasonable to hypothesize that categorization has, over tens of thousands of years, somehow proven useful for memory, communication, and organizational purposes in personkind.</p>
<p>As one might expect, speakers of gendered languages such as Spanish are more likely to categorize a feminine noun with stereotypically feminine conceptualizations,<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn17" id="fnref17">17</a></sup> e.g., <em>la</em> in Spanish is associated with the nouns that label girl, queen, nun, and so forth.  What was surprising was how speakers of English have established clear gender associations with formally ungendered adjectives and labels (presumably for the aforementioned organizational benefits).  For example, in Natsuki’s controlled study, the three words <em>pretty</em>, <em>careful</em>, and <em>nice</em> were given feminine conceptualizations by English-speaking people independent of gender, whereas <em>careless</em>, <em>happy</em>, and <em>messy</em> were conceptualized as masculine.  Of critical import, Fortson reminds us in his seminal textbook <em>Indo-European Language and Culture</em><sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn18" id="fnref18">18</a></sup> that every human learns language from scratch, matching sound patterns to meaning word-by-word instead of learning to understand rules of grammar or vocabulary. In this regard, languages with formal gender rules are not different than those without; infants make sense and categorize words according to what they hear and see.</p>
<p>Further to this line of thinking, English speakers have actually created new words to mark gender in some cases where existing words did not.  Consider the English word <em>actor</em>, entering Middle English in the late 14th century as “an overseer, guardian, steward” from Latin <em>actor</em>.  In the 1580s, its definition expanded to include "doer, “maker,” and attestations from those times are specifically noted by Etymonline<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn19" id="fnref19">19</a></sup> to have been epicene: applying to women, man, and animals without implying a gender.<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn20" id="fnref20">20</a></sup> Since <em>actor</em> did not indicate gender specifically and some English speakers presumably specifically desired to differentiate, English borrowed the -ess suffix from the French -esse (in turn from Latin -issa, Greek -ισσά) or perhaps the whole French word <em>actrice</em> to create the English word <em>actress</em>. Looking at the usage trends in Google ngrams<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn21" id="fnref21">21</a></sup>, the word <em>actress</em> reveals something astonishing: the word’s usage was reasonably stable at around 2.0/mm until 1960, when it more than <strong>doubled</strong> its usage to the current of 4.5/mm at a time when the feminist movement was surging.  English speakers were, and are, increasingly categorizing the word <em>actor</em> as masculine and <em>actresses</em> as feminine.</p>
<p>Consider <em>hero</em>, per Etymonline, “man of superhuman strength or physical courage,” taken from French &lt; Greek (ἥρως héros) &lt; PIE *ser- ‘to protect.’ <em>Heroine</em> was not introduced into English until 1650, borrowing from Latin, and is defined as “Heroic woman, woman distinguished by exalted courage or noble achievements.”  Usage of the word <em>heroine</em> peaked in 1900 at 4/mm, decreased to a low in 1940 of approximately 1.75/mm, and has steadily increased again to its current level of 3.0/mm. From Etymonline, Comedienne, an actress who plays comedy, appeared in English in 1849, borrowed from French. Its usage peaked in 1990 at 0.07/mm and has recently tailed off. These examples show that English speakers sometimes reflect a mental conceptualization of a category of a noun or adjective in language when unnecessary or previously absent.  Corbett refers to these in his other works as "lexical oppositions instantiated through derivational morphology,” meaning gendered versions of epicene words are produced through normal orthographical processes.</p>
<p>This behavior is not limited to English. For example Corbett writes more recently that German nouns of neuter gender can be inflected by speakers using what he calls “semantic agreement,” meaning applying masculine or femine agreements to a neuter noun. This is because the rules of German classify diminutives as neuter regardless of the gender of the base. Typically, dimunutives are formed by adding an umlaut to the vowel and adding -chen, resulting in a word that is automatically neuter.  Mädchen, meaning young maiden, is syntactically <strong>das</strong> Mädchen (neuter), though speakers may use feminine endings and pronouns since the referent is assumed to be female. When using an adjective and an indefinite article to describe a person, speakers have applied feminine endings (-e) rather than the neuter endings (null, -es). The speakers are applying gendered thinking in spite of syntactical rules.</p>
<p>Nouns and adjectives, in general, are associated with categories in the human mind, whether language rules require such categorization or not, and those arbitrary categories have come to be associated with biological sex.</p>
<h2 id="pie-third-person-personal-pronouns">PIE Third-Person Personal Pronouns</h2>
<p>Moving beyond nouns into the more specific world of pronouns, the categorization concept shifts from “arbitrary” toward the dozen or so gender-specific nouns applying to familial relationships, like woman, niece, daughter, sister, and aunt.  Even more specifically, personal pronouns apply to persons (first, second, third) and have traditionally be gendered accordering to biological sex.</p>
<p>According to the American Heritage Dictionary of Indo-European Roots,<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn22" id="fnref22">22</a></sup> the English pronoun <em>he</em> derives from the PIE root *h₁éyos- ‘he, that one.’  Etymonline, though, shows <em>he</em> as deriving from Proto-Germanic *hi-, itself a variant of the PIE root *ko- ‘this, here’.  Wiktionary quotes the PIE root of <em>he</em> as *ḱís- ‘this, here.’ Finally, OED ties the derivation back through Germanic languages, which in turn refer back to PIE for yet another interpretation.</p>
<p>To avoid confusion, the actual reconstructed pronouns themselves are detailed below rather than their reported ties to PIE roots. Considering phonological, orthographical, morphological, and syntactical changes, the third-person personal pronouns in many languages can be seen in the table below, sourced from Wikipedia.<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn23" id="fnref23">23</a></sup></p>
