</tr>
</tbody>
</table><h2 id="gender-neutral-pronouns-in-modern-english">Gender-Neutral Pronouns in Modern English</h2>
<p>First, in fairness to those who ask to be referenced by a pronoun other than the pronoun the syntactical rules of English would naturally select, it is important to note that most people using nearly any language feel an option, if not a right, to declare how they would like to be called, as their chosen name.  A name, while a proper noun and not a pronoun, is a label that serves an important role in language. My formal first name is Daniel, and I use <em>Dan</em> in English- and German-language contexts.  However, I generally use and request <em>Daniel</em> in Spanish- and Portuguese-language contexts because that name is more common and, more importantly, easier to pronounce.  Latin languages tend to have few words ending in a nasal or lingual stop, such as “n.”  Instead, they do have a relatively large number of words ending in the lateral approximate “l”.  In Portuguese, “l” is pronounced as a “w” and Daniel has the IPA transliteration of /dɐˈniɛw/.  In Spanish, the name Daniel yields the IPA transliteration of /daˈnjel/, where the alveolar nasal is immediately followed by the high front unrounded vowel, making it flow.  No one has ever thought it was odd that I would request to be referred to as Dan, Danny, or Daniel.</p>
<p>If a person has the natural liberty to request a specific proper noun as a referent, why, then, should a similar request regarding a pronoun be problematic?</p>
<p>The subtle difference is the use of nicknames or substitute proper nouns is frequently designed to improve the fluidity and ease of pronunciation of that proper noun.  Should that same objective be part of the determination of an alternate pronoun?</p>
<h3 id="they">They</h3>
<p>According to <a href="http://pronouns.org">pronouns.org</a>, the following sentence follows from the use of <em>they</em> as an epicene pronoun: “They are a writer and wrote that book themself. Those ideas are theirs. I like both them and their ideas.”</p>
<p>The use of <em>they</em> as an epicene (gender-neutral) pronoun in modern English<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn24" id="fnref24">24</a></sup> has a long and continuously evolving history (see Merriam-Webster<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn25" id="fnref25">25</a></sup> and the American Dialect Society<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn26" id="fnref26">26</a></sup>).  The use of the normally plural <em>they</em> to refer to a singular person has been attested since at least Middle English in the 14th Century<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn27" id="fnref27">27</a></sup>. For example, Geoffrey Chaucer used it in “The Canterbury Tales.”  <em>They</em> was employed to refer to an indefinite pronoun or a singular person whose gender was unknown or unspecified, though, importantly, it still retained its plural quality for agreement purposes.  In Early Modern English (16th - 17th Century), writers like William Shakespeare used “they” as a singular pronoun. In “The Comedy of Errors,” he wrote: “There’s not a man I meet but doth salute me / As if I were their well-acquainted friend.”  Later, during the 18th century, grammarians started promoting the use of <em>he</em> as a universal pronoun, which led to a decline in the use of the singular <em>they</em> in formal writing. (Studies<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn28" id="fnref28">28</a></sup> have shown that using <em>he</em> as a universal pronoun generally fails to satisfy any goals associated with epicene.) Nevertheless, the singular-referring plural-agreeing <em>they</em> persisted in colloquial usage and informal contexts.  In the 20th Century,  feminist movements highlighted the limitations of using <em>he</em> as a universal pronoun and advocated for more inclusive language. This renewed interest in using epicene <em>they</em> as a gender-neutral pronoun.</p>
<p>Recognizing that, though, omits the question of fluidity and pronounceability. The sentence “They are a writer and wrote that book themself. Those ideas are theirs. I like both them and their ideas" yields some awkwardness for English-speakers.  As a positive, the word “themself” would be more in agreement with the singular nature of they; however, the word is less familiar to native speakers and can be heard as awkward or even incorrect.  <em>They</em> as a plural referent coupled with the singular indefinite article “a” and singular “writer” can potentially cause an interruption in what would be an autonomic processing of the sentence below the conscious level.  In other words, the listener must break conscious processing mechanisms in the brain to fully understand the speaker.</p>
<p>Nonetheless, the use of so-called singular <em>they</em> has gained significant acceptance and recognition. Major style guides, such as the Associated Press (AP) and the Chicago Manual of Style, have acknowledged the validity of using <em>they</em> as a singular pronoun. In 2015, the American Dialect Society named singular <em>they</em> its Word of the Year. In 2019, Merriam-Webster added the non-binary use of <em>they</em> to its dictionary and named it the Word of the Year.</p>
<p>What remains unclear, though, is agreement (singular/plural) in other cases, such as the object, possessive, and reflexive forms.</p>
<h4 id="p-styletext-align-centertable-5---modern-english-epicene-third-person-personal-pronounsp"><p>Table 5 - Modern English Epicene Third-person Personal Pronouns</p></h4>

<table>
