<tr>
<th>Gender</th>
<th align="center">Number</th>
<th align="center">Nominative</th>
<th align="center">Object</th>
<th align="center">Genitive</th>
<th align="center">Reflexive</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>epicene</td>
<td align="center">singular</td>
<td align="center">they</td>
<td align="center">them</td>
<td align="center">their(s), <em>theys</em></td>
<td align="center">themselves, <em>themself</em></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>epicene</td>
<td align="center">plural</td>
<td align="center">they</td>
<td align="center">them</td>
<td align="center">their(s)</td>
<td align="center">themselves</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table><h3 id="neopronouns">Neopronouns</h3>
<p>Neopronouns are personal pronouns created to be used as alternatives to traditional pronouns. They are designed to provide gender-neutral options and respect the identities of people who do not identify as a binary gender or with their gender assigned at birth. These pronouns can be especially useful for non-binary, genderqueer, and other gender-nonconforming individuals.</p>
<p>There are many examples of neopronomical systems, using words such as ze, hir, xe, xem, ey, em, faer, faers, zher, and others.  Many such pronouns are driven by phonetic, syllabic, or rhythmic purposes, for example “Ze went to the store,” “I gave it to hir,” “It was zhers,” “I talked to xem yesterday,” “I met em at the event,” “This is faers book.” Each of those examples reflects a rhythmic and phonetic similarity to one or more of the existing pronouns, and rolls off the English-speaker’s tongue easily.</p>
<p>Among the more popular, or at least often discussed, are the so-called “ze” pronouns.  Purportedly influenced by the German “sie,” the feminine singular personal pronoun likely descending from a PIE root *h₁e- or *h₂e- (as previously mentioned, with morphology resulting in *sī in Proto-Germanic. Again, according to <a href="http://pronouns.org">pronouns.org</a>, there are two variants of ze pronouns, generally referred to as ze/hir and ze/zir.  For example, using ze/hir, one could say or write, “Ze is a writer and wrote that book hirself. Those ideas are hirs. I like both hir and hir ideas.” Similarly, using ze/zir pronouns, the following would be appropriate: "Ze is a writer and wrote that book zirself. Those ideas are zirs. I like both zir and zir ideas.”  There are also voiced versions of these pairs: zhe /ʒiː/ and zhir /ʒɪr/.</p>
<p>One concern about neopronouns is the lack of clarity around the forms to use in the few cases still required of personal pronouns: subject, object, possessive, and reflexive.  There is no natural affiliation with, for example, he, him, his, and himself. Such inflections must be clearly defined and then learned by rote memorization.  Given the contemporaneous deterioration of casing in pronouns, where current English speakers consistently mix object and subject case with personal pronouns (e.g., “her and I went to the store; me and him used to play basketball together”), it seems unlikely that native speakers could pick up new pronouns like this and learn increasingly ignored rules about inflecting according to case.</p>
<p>Finally, while English words certainly can be invented, and when invented, often do conform to rules of allomorphy, phonology, and orthography, it seems that such an enormously used word like <em>he</em> with a current ngram index of nearly 4000/mm would be irreplaceable if driven only by some at the grassroots level in the absence of some authoritative body governing the language.</p>
<p>The one <em>possible</em> wrinkle here in the case of “ze” is that an argument could potentially be made for a tie back to PIE roots.  Consider the third-person personal pronoun in a few PIE-derived languages below.  It does appear that <em>ze</em> could possibly be an allomorph of sorts for the feminine pronoun:</p>
<h4 id="p-styletext-align-centertable-7---possible-historical-association-with-ze-in-selected-pie-derivativesp"><p>Table 7 - Possible Historical Association with Ze in Selected PIE Derivatives</p></h4>

