</table><p>In April of 2015, hen<sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn29" id="fnref29">29</a></sup> was added to the official Swedish language dictionary Svenska Akademiens ordlista <sup class="footnote-ref"><a href="#fn30" id="fnref30">30</a></sup> of the Swedish Academy. Hen was purportedly inspired by the Finnish epicene third-person pronoun listed above. (Finnish is not derived from PIE and is therefore unrelated to the Scandinavian languages.) It is important to note that Swedes have used different natural morphologies of hen in different cases.  Hen was defined for nominative, and not necessarily other cases. For example, henom appears in written Swedish even though the intent was for hen to serve in the dative inflection.  Similarly, the possessive form was not necessarily defined, leaving Swedes to fall back on hens.</p>
<p>Thus, even <em>hen</em> suffers the awkwardness and ambiguity of neologisms.</p>
<h2 id="beyond-pronouns">Beyond Pronouns</h2>
<p>Modern Latinate languages use specific endings to indicate gender for many parts of speech, and there has been a movement to neutralize gender by using an epicene “-e” in place of the “-o” or “-a” typically found in nouns.</p>
<h4 id="p-styletext-align-centertable-10---latinate-typical-nounadjective-endingsp"><p>Table 10 - Latinate Typical Noun/Adjective Endings</p></h4>

<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Language</th>
<th>Masculine</th>
<th>Feminine</th>
<th>Plural</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td><strong>Spanish</strong></td>
<td>-o</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-os, -as</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Portuguese</strong></td>
<td>-o</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-os, -as</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Italian</strong></td>
<td>-o</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-i , -e</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Galician</strong></td>
<td>-o</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-os, -as</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Catalan</strong></td>
<td>-o, -e</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-s, -es</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Occitan</strong></td>
<td>-o, -e</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-s, -as</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Sardinian</strong></td>
<td>-u, -e</td>
<td>-a</td>
<td>-os, -as</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Romanian</strong></td>
<td>-u, -e</td>
<td>-ǎ, -e</td>
<td>-i, -e</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>French</strong></td>
<td>-e, -age, -ment</td>
<td>-e, -ion, té</td>
<td>-s, unchanged</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table><p>One way to highlight this Latinate issue is to use an “@” to replace the ending gender-implying vowel, yielding, for example, latin@, amig@, or estudient@ (both a male and female student are estudiantes; however, using the article <em>el</em> or <em>la</em> changes the gender, so this notation is used to imply an unspecified sex).  Sentences then render as, for example, L@s niñ@s están jugando en el parque (the children are playing at the park).</p>
<p>Another growing yet controversial method is to replace the indicator “o” or “a” with an “e.”  For example, instead of “latino” or “latina,” write or say “<strong>latine</strong>” /latiː’neɪ/ to serve as an epicene noun.  This desire to eliminate the -o or -a is also likely the genesis of the English expression “Latinx” to mean Latino, Latina, Latine, or Latin@.  Criticisms of the use of word Latinx, based on personal conversations with members of the Latinate-speaking community, are that it follows none of the thousands of years of language traditions and cannot even be pronounced in the target languages. Its construction practically begs a white-male tech-inspired origin, where the letter x is supposed to be substituted by some other letter as in algebra or software. Importantly to native Spanish speakers, the letter “x” is not part of Modern Spanish , which has changed significantly since the Real Academia Española introduced orthographical simplifications in the 18th century. The letter is used only in geographical names or other words rooted in deep history.  In other words, “x” is deprecated in Spanish.  I have yet to find a native speaker of Spanish or Portuguese that has warmed to the term Latinx and, indeed, have found criticism that the expression LatinX is a device invented, and used, by non-native speakers uninformed of  the original role of gender as simply a noun classification device.</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>In conclusion, my two initial hypotheses are disproven.  The first, that English is already practically gender-free is simply not true.  Gendered nouns exist in English and are important in familial relationships, honorifics, personal pronouns, and even speaker-driven creations like actresses are created when necessary.  More importantly, humans categorize words naturally into genders whether the language prescribes it or not.  When gender is descoped to its original meaning of noun categorization, it seems that the kind of gender elimination pressured by activism is independent of whether a language is gendered or otherwise inflectionally complex.</p>
<p>Similarly, my hypothesis that an epicene pronoun or a neologism designed to defeat sex-linked associations could be phonetically or rhythmically similar to existing pronouns to become widespread and useful is incorrect. The universal properties of language: inflection, case, and agreement, still apply, and unless an epicene pronoun can be developed that is consistent with those propertiesa and then be memorized by millions, phonetic and rhythmic similarities alone are insufficient to achieve the goal.</p>
<p>Using <em>they</em> to refer to a single referent is accepted though does not need to be overly complex. My recommendation to those choosing <em>they</em> it to use the word as it is, including agreement and casing and break only the syntactical rule of number. “They wrote a book by themselves, and their book gave them fame.”  I do not recommend trying to create “themself” or “theys” or other attempts to fix the number problem in cases other than nominative because it introduces more trouble than benefit.</p>
<p>In the end, though, the aims of those seeking an epicene pronoun may not be fully aligned with the real changes sought.  In my personal opinion, the path to eliminating gender bias in language is not through altering pronouns, which would do nothing for categorization processes embedded in all speakers, instead, it relies on careful and thoughtful awareness of unconscious bias resulting in careful and thoughtful application of language <em>within</em> its bounds.  For example, referring to humans or persons, and avoiding stereotyped role association, using she when referring to unknown users, customers, clients, etc.  The problematic consequences of gender stereotyping are in the mind, not the language.</p>
<p>We must work to make our own internal bias more conscious and express ourselves in our own language to make lasting change.</p>
